                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d441">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">White</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-12-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 20, 1902</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Mr. White states that the supplement to the London Gazette of December 20, 1902,
                    contains the following notice only: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>It is hereby notified that as the United States of Venezuela have failed
                            to comply with the demands of His Majesty’s Government, a blockade by
                            His Majesty’s naval forces on the ports of La Guayra, Carenero, Guanta,
                            Cumana, Carupano, and the mouths of the Orinoco is declared, and such
                            blockade will be effectively maintained from and after the 25th day of
                            December, subject to an allowance of the following days of grace for
                            vessels sailing before the date of this notification. From West Indian
                            ports and from ports on the east coast of the continent of America, ten
                            days for steamers and twenty days for sailing vessels; from all other
                            points, twenty days for steamers and forty days for sailing vessels; for
                            vessels lying in ports now declared to be blockaded, fifteen days.
                            Vessels which attempt to violate the blockade will render themselves
                            liable to all measures authorized by the law of nations and the
                            respective treaties between His Majesty’s Government and the different
                            neutral powers.)</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
